Business Scenario¶

RestoreMasters is a car restoration company based in New York, USA.

Within short span of time, this company has become renowned for restoring vintage cars.

Their team takes great pride in each of their projects, no matter how big or small. They offer paint jobs, frame build-ups, engine restoration, body work etc. They restore cars of various origins including USA, Europe and Asia

The management wants to expand their business by increasing the capacity of the number of cars that can be restored.

They want to generate greater revenue for the company through cost cutting and providing a data driven approach to their current process.

They feel that the insights from existing data will help them in making data-driven decisions and also automate some of the key tasks in the process.

Key Objectives:

  1. Getting Insights to make data-driven business decisions.
    Example: Decision to decentralize restoration work with specialized facility.

  2. Usage of Machine learning models that can help in automating important tasks.
    Example:

    • Predicting the mileage of incoming cars
    • Automated classification of incoming cars

In Python, Code organization is done through modules and packages.

A Module is a python file with a .py extension.

A package is a folder which contains modules.

Package can store many python modules/files in it.

Before we make use of the packages, we need to import them using “import” command into the workspace. To ease the usage, packages are imported with alias names.

Standard alias names are ‘np’ for numpy, ‘pd’ for pandas and ‘plt’ for matplotlib.pyplot

Step 1: Importing the dataset¶

In [6]:
# importing the dataset to Pandas DataFrame: cars_df
cars_df=pd.read_csv('cars93.csv')

A Pandas DataFrame is a two-dimensional data structure that stores data in a tabular format of rows and columns.

Every column in a DataFrame is a Pandas Series object.

Pandas DataFrame object contains attributes and methods. Attributes represents the characteristics. Example: shape, dtype Methods represents the actions that can be carried on DataFrame. Example: info(), describe()

Pandas can read a variety of files.

For example:

a table of fixed width formatted lines (read_fwf), excel sheets (read_excel), html files (read_html), json files (read_json)

Step 3: Handling Missing Values¶

Datasets can contain missing values. This can be handled in 2 ways:

  1. Remove missing values. Rows or columns containing missing values can be removed.

    pandas.DataFrame.dropna() method can be used to drop missing values in the DataFrame. It takes the axis parameter which can have two values 0 or 1

    If axis=0 , it will drop rows containing missing values If axis=1, it will drop columns containing missing values

  1. Replacing the missing values with new values . This is also called as imputation.

pandas.DataFrame.isna() method helps in detecting missing values in the DataFrame. Method returns the entire DataFrame object with boolean values.

Values in the DataFrame such as NaN and None will be mapped as ‘True’ and all other values are mapped as ‘False’

pandas.DataFrame.any(axis=0) method checks if any element consists of Boolean – ‘True’ over columns

Method reduces the index and returns the Series object with column names as index.

Indexing and Selecting data in DataFrame

Row index labels and column labels helps in identifying the data in a DataFrame. It helps in getting and setting the subsets of dataset.

Pandas supports three types of indexing:

[] – basic indexing

.loc – label based

.iloc – position based

Selecting data using [ ]

  1. Selecting a single column of the DataFrame: cars_df

    Single column name can be passed to DataFrame to select the respective column

    Example:cars_df['name']

  1. Selecting a multiple columns of the DataFrame: cars_df

    List of multiple column names can be passed to the DataFrame to select the columns in given order

    Example:cars_df[['name','mpg','horsepower']]

  1. Filtering the specific rows in the DataFrame: cars_df

    conditional expressions can be specified inside the [ ] to select the rows based on conditions. Here the conditional expression will be evaluated to Boolean ‘True’/’False’. Returns only rows having boolean ‘True’.

    Example:cars_df[cars_df['mpg']<=10]

In [19]:
# Replacing missing values with mean horsepower of cars with similar cylinders and model_year
cars_df['horsepower'] = cars_df.groupby(['cylinders', 'model_year'])['horsepower'].apply(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))

pandas.DataFrame.fillna() method can be used to fill NA or NaN values in the DataFrame. There are various methods for imputing the numerical and categorical columns. Numerical columns can be imputed with mean, median etc. Categorical columns can be imputed with mode and so on.

pandas.DataFrame.groupby() method helps in splitting the dataset into groups and then performing operations on those groups.

When groupby() is applied on the column(s) of the DataFrame, following steps are performed:

  • Split : splitting the dataset into groups
  • Apply: applying operations to each group. Aggregation, Transformation and Filtration operations can be applied
  • Combine: combining the results to the DataFrame

Example:cars_df.groupby('cylinders')['mpg'].mean()

Grouping data on multiple columns

Example:cars_df.groupby(['cylinders','model_year'])['mpg'].mean()

lambda functions are in-line functions or anonymous functions.

Example:

mpg=[35,10,8,20]
print(list(map(lambda x: 'Good' if x>15 else 'Bad',mpg)))
print(list(filter(lambda x: x>15,mpg)))

output: ['Good', 'Bad', 'Bad', 'Good']
        [35, 20]

pandas.DataFrame.apply() method applies a given function along the axis of the DataFrame. By default it will be applied along axis=0.

Step 6: Handling outliers¶

Finding Outliers using graphical analysis¶

Matplotlib is one of the most basic and popular Python libraries used for data visualization.

Basic elements of Matplotlib plots:

  • Figure: The Figure is the top-level container . A figure can contain multiple axes.
  • Axes: The Axes is the area on which data is plotted. There can be multiple axes in a figure. But a given axes object can only be in one figure. In a two-dimensional plot, axes contain 2 axis objects, title, x-label, and y-label.
  • Axis: The Axis takes care of data limits. axis consists of ticks and respective tick labels

Handling outliers in horespower and acceleration columns of the DataFrame: cars_df¶
In [31]:
# finding the upper and lower limit of horespower and acceleration columns

def find_outlier_limits(col_name):
    Q1,Q3=cars_df[col_name].quantile([.25,.75])
    IQR=Q3-Q1
    low=Q1-(1.5* IQR)
    high=Q3+(1.5* IQR)
    return (high,low)

high_hp,low_hp=find_outlier_limits('horsepower')
print('Horsepower: ','upper limit: ',high_hp,' lower limit: ',low_hp)
high_acc,low_acc=find_outlier_limits('acceleration')
print('Acceleration: ','upper limit: ',high_acc,' lower limit:',low_acc)

# Replacing outlier values in horespower and acceleration columns with respective 
# upper and lower limits

cars_df.loc[cars_df['horsepower']>high_hp,'horsepower']=high_hp
cars_df.loc[cars_df['acceleration']>high_acc,'acceleration']=high_acc
cars_df.loc[cars_df['acceleration']<low_acc,'acceleration']=low_acc

Horsepower:  upper limit:  200.0  lower limit:  0.0
Acceleration:  upper limit:  22.2  lower limit: 8.8

.loc and .iloc operators are used to select specific set of rows and columns in a DataFrame.

.loc operator can be used with row labels and column labels. Conditional expressions returning boolean can also be passed as row labels.

Example:cars_df.loc[cars_df['mpg']<=10,'name']

.iloc operator can be used with row positions and column positions

Example:cars_df.iloc[10:20,0:3]

.iloc operator can be used to filter rows based on conditional expressions

Example:cars_df.iloc[cars_df.index[cars_df['cylinders']==3]]

In [67]:
model_origin_df=cars_df.groupby(['model_year','origin'])[['name']].count().reset_index().rename(columns={'name':'cars_count'})
# visualize origin wise - year and car_count (line)
#creating an empty canvas/figure
fig = plt.figure(figsize=[5,5]) #figsize represents width and height in inches. Default value is [6.4, 4.8]
#Adding single axes to the figure 
ax1 = fig.add_axes([0, 0, 1, 1]) #The dimensions [left, bottom, width, height] of the new Axes with respect to figure size
model_origin_df[model_origin_df['origin']=='usa'].plot( ax=ax1, x = "model_year", y = "cars_count",kind = "line",color='green', linewidth=4, label='USA' )
model_origin_df[model_origin_df['origin']=='japan'].plot(ax=ax1, x = "model_year", y = "cars_count",kind = "line",color='blue', linewidth=4, label='Japan' )

pandas.DataFrame.corr() method calculates the pairwise correlation of columns.

Correlation scores helps in defining the linear relationship between the two columns. Coorrelation is measured using correlation coefficient.

  • Positive values of correlation coefficient indicate that the values of both columns tend to increase together resulting in Positive correlation
  • Negative values of correlation coefficient indicate that when values of one column increases, the values of other decreases resulting in Negative correlation.

Step3: Train and Test data split¶

The data must be divided into two parts. First, a training set on which model can be trained. Second, a testing set on which the model can be validated.

sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split() method divides the predictors (X) and the corresponding targets (y) into train data (X_train, y_train) and test data (X_test, y_test). It is a general practice to consider 20% of data for testing (test_size=0.2).

In [85]:
# train test split
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 0)

Certain algorithms work well when all the columns are on the same scale. In order to achieve this, data can normalized using various scaler available in Scikit Learn library, such as Standard scaler, MinMax scaler, etc.

When applying any transformation to the data, Scikit Learn applys the transformation in two phases - fit phase and transform phase. During the fit phase, the parameters required for the transformation are learnt. During the transform phase, the data is actually modified or altered.

Generally the fit phase is carried out with train data, and the parameters learnt are applied to transform both the train and the test data.

In [86]:
#Applying standard scaler on the data
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scale = StandardScaler()
scale.fit_transform(X_train)
scale.transform(X_test);
Step4: Training the model¶

The Linear Regression model is used to build the model. A linear regression model uses the following equation:

y = B0 + B1X1 + B2X2 + + Bn*Xn

y refers to the target and X1,X2…..Xn refer to the predictors. B0 is the intercept and B1,B2…..Bn are the coefficients.

Below code demonstrates the Linear Regression model building using sklearn library on the training data set.

In [87]:
#Importing the algorithm

Classification model¶

Predictors and Target:

  • The predictors are the variables that are used to predict the target. All columns excluding name and company are considered as predictors.
  • The target variable is 'car_type' which has to be predicted.

Step3: Train and Test data split¶

The data must be divided into two parts. First, a training set on which model can be trained. Second, a testing set on which the model can be validated.

In [98]:
#train test split
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 0)
In [99]:
#Applying standard scaler on the data

Step4: Training the model¶

The KNeighborsClassifier is used to build the classification model.

Below code demonstrates the classification model building using sklearn library on the training data set.

In [100]:
#Importing the algorithm
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5,metric="euclidean")
In [101]:
#Fitting the model on training data
classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[101]:
KNeighborsClassifier(metric='euclidean')
Step5: Testing the model¶

The trained lclassification model is used for prediction against the training and testing data set.

In [102]:
#Predicting the target: mpg against the predictors in the training data set
#Predicted data stored in y_pred_train
y_pred_train = classifier.predict(X_train)
In [103]:
#Predicting the target: mpg against the predictors in the testing data set
#Predicted data stored in y_pred_test
y_pred_test = classifier.predict(X_test)
Step6: Evaluating Model Performance¶

There are different metrics used to evaluate the performance of the model. Here the accuracy score is used.
